post_cb({"9545279": {"ParentId": "9545208", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "7", "CreationDate": "2012-03-03T10:16:51.793", "Score": "17", "LastEditorUserId": "366904", "LastEditDate": "2012-03-03T10:22:31.183", "Id": "9545279", "OwnerUserId": "168175", "Body": "<p>In C++</p>\n<pre><code>void f(void);\n</code></pre>\n<p>is identical to:</p>\n<pre><code>void f();\n</code></pre>\n<p>The fact that the first style can still be legally written can be attributed to C.<br>\nn3290 \u00a7 C.1.7 (C++ and ISO C compatibility) states:</br></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_9545208_9545279_0\"><strong>Change</strong>: In C++, a function declared with an empty parameter list takes\n  no arguments.</p>\n<p id=\"so_9545208_9545279_1\">In C, an empty parameter list means that the number and\n  type of the function arguments are unknown.</p>\n<p id=\"so_9545208_9545279_2\">Example: </p>\n<pre><code>int f(); // means int f(void) in C++\n         // int f( unknown ) in C\n</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In C, it makes sense to avoid that undesirable \"unknown\" meaning. In C++, it's superfluous. </p>\n<p>Short answer: in C++ it's a hangover from too much C programming. That puts it in the \"don't do it unless you really have to\" bracket for C++ in my view.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-03-03T10:22:31.183"}, "9545269": {"ParentId": "9545208", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>I <em>feel like</em> no. Reasons:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A lot more code out there has the <code>BOOL Translate()</code> form, so others reading your code will be more comfortable and productive with it.</li>\n<li>Having less on the screen (especially something redundant like this) means less thinking for somebody reading your code.</li>\n<li>Sometimes people, who didn't program in C in 1988, ask \"What does <code>foo(void)</code> mean?\"</li>\n</ul>\n", "OwnerUserId": "660284", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "9545269", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2012-03-03T10:15:00.247", "LastActivityDate": "2012-03-03T10:15:00.247"}, "22092397": {"ParentId": "9545208", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>Just as a side note. Another reason for not including the void is that software, like starUML,  that can read code and generate class diagrams, read the void as a parameter. Even though this may be a flaw in the UML generating software, it is still annoying to have to go back and remove the \"void\"s if you want to have clean diagrams</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "3364372", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "22092397", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-02-28T10:25:45.343", "LastActivityDate": "2014-02-28T10:25:45.343"}, "9545229": {"ParentId": "9545208", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>I see absolutely no reason for this. IDEs will just complete the function call with an empty argument list, and 4 characters less.</p>\n<p>Personally I believe this is making the already verbose C++ even more verbose. There's no version of the language I'm aware of that requires the use of <code>void</code> here.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "256138", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "9545229", "Score": "6", "CreationDate": "2012-03-03T10:09:52.087", "LastActivityDate": "2012-03-03T10:09:52.087"}, "9545228": {"ParentId": "9545208", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>I think it will only help in backward compatibility with older C code, otherwise it is redundant.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1151151", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "9545228", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2012-03-03T10:09:35.590", "LastActivityDate": "2012-03-03T10:09:35.590"}, "9545208": {"CommentCount": "3", "AcceptedAnswerId": "9545279", "CreationDate": "2012-03-03T10:06:00.460", "LastActivityDate": "2014-02-28T10:25:45.343", "PostTypeId": "1", "ViewCount": "8956", "FavoriteCount": "1", "Title": "Using void in functions without parameter?", "Id": "9545208", "Score": "10", "Body": "<p>In C++ using <code>void</code> in a function with no parameter, for example:</p>\n<pre><code>class WinMessage\n{\npublic:\n    BOOL Translate(void);\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>is redundant, you might as well just write  <code>Translate();</code>.</p>\n<p>I, myself generally include it since it's a bit helpful when code-completion supporting IDEs display a <code>void</code>, since it ensures me that the function takes definitely no parameter. </p>\n<p>My question is, Is adding <code>void</code> to parameter-less functions a good practice? Should it be encouraged in modern code?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><function><methods><void>", "OwnerUserId": "753341", "AnswerCount": "5"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_9545208_9545279_1": {"section_id": 3240, "quality": 0.6666666666666666, "length": 6}, "so_9545208_9545279_0": {"section_id": 3240, "quality": 0.625, "length": 5}}, "n3337": {"so_9545208_9545279_1": {"section_id": 3113, "quality": 0.6666666666666666, "length": 6}, "so_9545208_9545279_0": {"section_id": 5541, "quality": 0.625, "length": 5}}, "n4659": {"so_9545208_9545279_1": {"section_id": 3996, "quality": 0.6666666666666666, "length": 6}}}});